<p><b>Daniel Ellsberg</b> (born April 7, 1931) is a former American military analyst employed by the <a href="/wiki/RAND_Corporation" title="RAND Corporation" class="mw-redirect">RAND Corporation</a> who precipitated a national political controversy in 1971 when he released the <i><a href="/wiki/Pentagon_Papers" title="Pentagon Papers">Pentagon Papers</a>,</i> a <a href="/wiki/Classified_information" title="Classified information">top-secret</a> <a href="/wiki/The_Pentagon" title="The Pentagon">Pentagon</a> study of government decision-making about the <a href="/wiki/Vietnam_War" title="Vietnam War">Vietnam War</a>, to <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">The New York Times</a></i> and other newspapers.</p>
